\'93This way,\'94 Hargrave called, rounding a corner at the end of the hall.\
He went up a flight of stairs, Roderick following as quickly as he could manage. His lungs burned, his mortal fear of exercise out-won by a more driving fear\'97that he would be eaten alive, or ravaged by cold, dead hands\'97or worse still, that he would be bitten and infected. The idea of his rational thoughts devolving into predatory instinct terrified him. Desperate, his feet hammered up the staircase, up two flights of steps.\
